cn:association.description: CNBC's "Futures Now," is the first multi-platform media experience entirely devoted to the futures market. From gold to gas to S&P, the "Futures Now" crew will teach you how to harness the power of the multi-trillion dollar futures market, and turn today's events into tomorrow's profits.

cn:association.cn:title: Oil prices slip further after sell-off on demand concern and rising US output
cn:association.cn:summary: Oil prices continued to slip on Thursday as traders looked ahead to the OPEC meeting at the end of this month.
cn:association.cn:linkHeadline: Oil prices slip further after sell-off on demand concern and rising US output
cn:association.headline: Oil prices slip further after sell-off on demand concern and rising US output
cn:association.cn:shorterHeadline: Oil slips further after sell-off on demand concern, rising US output
cn:association.cn:shorterDescription: Oil prices continued to slip on Thursday as traders looked ahead to the OPEC meeting at the end of this month.
cn:association.cn:shortestDescription: Oil prices continued to slip on Thursday as traders looked ahead to the OPEC meeting at the end of this month.
cn:association.cn:bodyTeaser:
Oil prices continued to slip on Thursday as traders looked ahead to the OPEC meeting at the end of this month, when many expect producers to extend output cuts.

Brent crude oil was down 43 cents a barrel at $61.44 by 9:37 a.m. ET (1337 GMT). U.S. light crude fell 29 cents to $55.04.

Crude futures have mostly risen over the past few months as the impact of OPEC-led supply cuts has drained inventories.

But prices have slipped in recent days from the two-year highs hit last week by both crude benchmarks after signs that U.S. supply is rising fast and could potentially undermine OPEC's efforts to tighten the market.

Concerns about consumption also emerged after the International Energy Agency cut its forecast for demand growth in 2017 and 2018.
